text:
nyc and la!  i want to invite you to a free screening tomorrow morning.  it’s first come, first served. 
a message from all about nina director, eva vives: “when i wrote this movie i knew i wasn’t alone, but not much had been said publicly about the trauma and troubles that survivors go through. this week, despite the powerful #metoo movement, we continue to see the fight that women have to put up in order to be believed.

i am a survivor. i believe survivors. and i believe that having our voices and stories heard is important. i realize that a film might not be able to solve all the problems in the world but i also know that growing up, sitting in the dark watching stories unfold in front of me, i felt less afraid and more hopeful.

representation matters. i made this film for you.”
- eva vives

text:
to the brave survivors who are sharing their stories this week: i stand with you, and i feel you. now - it’s time to heal. i hope this self-care sequence brings a sense of security to anyone feeling triggered by the current news cycle. link in bio to read the full article. thank you, @yogajournal for inviting me to share my story, and for keeping this dialogue open in the yoga community. 💜
—————————————
although there is still an element of shame in sharing my story, i know now that i don’t have to run away from it. i have gained a sense of resilience from this experience. through my personal yoga and meditation practice, i have learned how to live in, respond to, and honor the sensations of my body. no matter what arises, i have the capacity to hold space for it. it is in the tolerance of our feelings that creates our ability to heal. @exhale2inhale @ishtayoga .
#itstimetoheal #timesup #believesurvivors #metoo #yoga #empower #heal #courage #ishtayoga #unboundpotential

text:
in 2012 i did rounds at a hospice center in glendale. under my care was a 98 year old woman. her & i always enjoyed each other’s company.
one day, while telling me stories of her childhood, she told me how she was raped in a drive-in movie theatre when she was about 16. she said she thought he was “a nice boy”, but he violently assaulted her. she told me “girls couldn’t speak about that then”. she then told me i was the only person to hear this story.
this woman was raped in 1930 and waited 82 years before she told a single soul.
i’m sure she has passed on. & i’m glad, because i can’t imagine telling her that today, in 2018, girls still can’t speak about it.  #metoo #isurvived #fuckpatriarchy #endrape

text:
my overwhelming thoughts from yesterday are: i believe dr. christine blasey ford. she is brave beyond measure. i am sick over what happened to her in high school, and what she has had to endure for all of her years following. now she is facing death threats during a time that she is having to relive her attack more vividly and more completely than ever before. she felt so strongly compelled to do her civic duty by telling the truth about her attacker, that she chose to make her trauma public and put herself in danger. no woman, child, or man should ever have to go through what she has gone through.

the reality is that more of us will go through what she is going through. more of us will be raped, sexually assaulted, or sexually harassed. plenty of us already have been. inevitably some of our attackers will seek positions of power, and more people will be faced with the choice that dr. ford was forced to make. that is terrifying. 
thinking about her decision i was reminded of the train dilemma. do you switch the tracks to run over one person and save the lives of five other people, or do you do nothing and allow for the 5 to be killed? i believe dr. ford was the one person on the other track and she switched the track anyways. 
thank you dr. christine blasey ford. thank you for the truth. 
#metoo #believesurvivors

text_retweet:
this is where i am at. to the men in my life, i love you and appreciate your support and in the coming days we're sitting down to have  seriously interesting conversations about how you show up. for some, you represent a father-figure in more ways than you expect.  that is the role you took on when my biological father walked out on my mom, sister, and i. for others you are my extended family and i chose you to be in my life.  @glennondoyle said it best so i'm reposting: i'm not sure what we do about the bad men, yet. but it’s past time to call up the good men. 
good men- don’t support us privately. that is no support at all. 
if you believe in our humanity- if you believe our trauma-
if you believe our shared government should protect us all- 
not because we are your daughters or sisters or wives but because we are human beings. 
speak up. use your platforms. they might yell at you. they might laugh at you. they might dismiss you and tell you that you’re crazy. 
when that happens- you’ll know you’ve joined us. but not until then.
call the teachers the husbands the brothers the church leaders the coaches....call the good men up, sisters. good is as good does. #goodmen #timesup #metoo #novemberiscoming #believesurvivors

tweet_full:
this is where i am at. to the men in my life, i love you and appreciate your support and in the coming days we're sitting down to have  seriously interesting conversations about how you show up. for some, you represent a father-figure in more ways than you expect.  that is the role you took on when my biological father walked out on my mom, sister, and i. for others you are my extended family and i chose you to be in my life.  @glennondoyle said it best so i am reposting: i am not sure what we do about the bad men, yet. but it’s past time to call up the good men. 
good men- don’t support us privately. that is no support at all. 
if you believe in our humanity- if you believe our trauma-
if you believe our shared government should protect us all- 
not because we are your daughters or sisters or wives but because we are human beings. 
speak up. use your platforms. they might yell at you. they might laugh at you. they might dismiss you and tell you that you’re crazy. 
when that happens- you’ll know you’ve joined us. but not until then.
call the teachers the husbands the brothers the church leaders the coaches....call the good men up, sisters. good is as good does. #goodmen #timesup #metoo #novemberiscoming #believesurvivors

text:
this week was hard and for so many of us, yesterday was fucking brutal.
.
in light of the madness this week has brought here are a few heading into this weekend:
.
- let yourself feel what you need to. let it hurt, let yourself be as angry as you need to be, as hurt, as vulnerable.
- let yourself cry.
- share your story if it serves you.
- unplug and take a time out from the media onslaught.
- do some yoga, take a walk, move your body a bit.
- spend time with people you love, do your fave things, get outside, eat good food, drink all the coffee, read a book, whatever makes you feel good.
- register to vote.
.
remember that you are a fucking warrior but that doesn’t mean you have to fight every day.
.
remember that bravery can also be found in gentleness.
.
whatever you do this weekend, just do whatever you need to do to protect yourself.
.

text_retweet:
#repost @wisetobewild with @get_repost
・・・
today with a quivering voice, i heard dr. christine blasey ford admit she was terrified and proceed with her testimony anyway. although i have always been in support of the me-too movement, i never really shared my own story. but something about her courage makes me want to finally say #metoo. ⠀
⠀
its happened more than once. in momentary awkward ways that made me feel embarrassed and small. it's happened in catastrophic ways that left me sobbing with a sense of shame that sat in my stomach for years. my abusers were strangers, acquaintances, co-workers, people i thought were my friends and even people i thought loved me.⠀
⠀
why i didn't report.....because not only was i in denial but the entire world around me was as well. just like my culture blamed me, i also blamed myself. ⠀
⠀
but i do not say this as a victim but as a survivor. each time i got back up, healed the wound, and learned how to love and trust again.⠀
⠀
to all the survivors- you're not alone. although the world might try to deny, accuse, attack, berate and belittle- i hear your story, i believe your truth and i stand with you. courage is contagious. thank you to all of the hundreds of thousands who gave me the courage i have today. ⠀
⠀
⠀

⠀
⠀
⠀
⠀

text:
we are all survivors of various forms of sexual harassment/assault/violence and in our own ways, all in recovery from the patriarchal capitalist systems that are rooted in violence against women. .
.
i am still tracing my own trauma to its roots; to this day i am more quiet about my personal experiences of sexual violence and harassment than i am of other sexually related trauma, i.e. abortions. .
.
i have remained quiet because somehow i still identify my own participation in the experiences i’ve had and also because i feel what i’ve experienced is far less violent than what many others have endured or are experiencing now. .
.
yet the truth is clear to me that what i’ve experienced is symptomatic of the patriarchy, and that the intersection of health sovereignty, environmental justice, and justice for all these survivors of sexual assault are deeply interwoven. .
.
we must hold these perpetrators accountable and we must recognize oppressive system and the paradigm that generates these assaults on us, our communities and our planet.
.
.
i am still finding my voice and learning to trust my boundaries and release fear for asking to be respected. .
.
today i am proud to be a survivor and to be in recovery, to be a woman and inspired to do my part .
.
#thankyouchristineblaseyford #shero #metoo #survivor #intersectionalfeminism

text:
this week, dude. so many women including myself are holding our breath and reliving stories we’d rather bury. trauma and post traumatic stress disorder is still a widely misunderstood concept - it affects the brain on a neurological level, especially the hippocampus (memories) and amygdala (fear response), and it’s vital to extend compassion and empathy towards survivors.
i want to applaud those who came forward with their stories with the likes of #metoo and #whyididntreport, and honor those who aren’t ready to share their story. these past few weeks have dug up unresolved trauma and rage; please take care of yourselves. turn off the tv/social media if you need to. and check in with each other. ♥️

text_retweet:
#repost @janayaforthefuture (@get_repost) thank you to @janayaforthefuture for your clarity always. ・・・
it has never been about the credibility of women. 
dr. christine blasey ford withstood an impossible degree of scrutiny to prove to the world that kavanaugh, the man seeking a lifetime appointment in the supreme court (highest court in the land), had sexually assaulted her in high school.

dr blasey ford is from the same elite society as brett kavanaugh. but it wasn’t enough. to america, her power is only diminished by an unfortunate circumstance of gender. to be ‘credible’ as a woman is still considered less than an untrustworthy, angry and predatory man. 
dr. blasey ford has been courageous and despite the disgusting response from the gop and many from the right, she is hailed as a hero among the political left. 
27 years ago, law professor anita hill also courageously testified during a supreme court confirmation process. she made it clear that judge clarence thomas had sexually harassed her and acted on her civic duty to tell the truth. anita hill was not considered ‘credible’, nor was she embraced by the political left. she was attacked and vilified across the country. were it not for women like anita hill, we would not have movements like #metoo now.

we must shift our need to sacrifice certain women so that others can be empowered. this isn’t when we give up, it’s when we learn and grow and do things differently. 
that kavanaugh will be confirmed, i have no doubt. but i want to remind y’all that this does not mean we lost the fight. on the contrary, the real fight is just getting started. there will always be men like kavanaugh and his enablers in the pipeline and at the end of it, when it counts, a powerful force of women to stop them. every time we fight, we win. 
#anitahill #stopkavanaugh #believesurvivors #christineblaseyford

text:
september 28, 2018, in solidarity #ibelievedrford: 
you have seen me facedown in the dirt
hungry for a rebel mouth, finding only
ashes spit from my mother’s parched
throat, my grandmother’s hollow lips. 
when our voices held no value,
when the abuses became normal, when
the shame and blame were charred stumps
we held them alone, our tongues blistering
at the edges of silence. 
for the women who spoke and were ignored,
who spoke and were shamed,
who spoke and lost jobs,
who spoke and faced violence,
for the women who survived in silence: 
we must bear witness to our stories,
to the isolation of women who never
heard the words me too. 
my silence echoes off the soft skin of my
daughter and it sounds like a scream. 
and i know in this moment that i cannot leave my pain.
to speak of it is an act of resistance and there is more
to my story than the wreckage. 
i hold my daughter’s hand and scream
streaked brilliance uplifted by the wind,
may she never doubt her voice is power. 
this, my love, is the beginning of a promise:
the essence of invisibility dies here. 
these lines are excerpts from the poem sea and stone  #webelievedrford  #ibelieveher #metoo #poetry #poems #believesurvivors #whyididntreport #istandwithdrford

text:
this week i experienced every possible emotion one could imagine. i don’t have it in me to rehash the struggle, but i do want to share a few of those feelings—namely, gratitude and pride.
.
i’m insanely grateful and so incredibly proud to be one of the four speakers at @amberrose’s slutwalk next weekend. @slutwalk_la is a protest calling to end rape culture, including much of what we saw this week—from victim blaming to slut shaming of sexual assault victims. specifically, we walk to crush the ignorant mindset that a woman is “asking for it” based on her appearance.
.
as a woman and a black woman, i know what it’s like to be disparaged, degraded and hyper-sexualized based on your appearance and, at times, your very existence. it means the world to me to have the opportunity to speak truth and life to a crowd of 20,000+ dope people, many of whom are fighting to take back their power and to overcome sexist stigmata.
.
thank you, amber, for leading the way for women in la, for letting this ballsy and overly excited do-gooder be a part of your dream, and for unifying and uplifting women of all walks. and thank you to the @amberrosefoundation for your very existence.
.
please do join us on saturday, oct. 6 as we take over pershing square in downtown la and as we elevate our voices to make change in the midst of this trying time 🌹⚖️🔥👠 ticket info is available at www.amberroseslutwalk.com 
#slutwalk #kavanaugh #equality #stepup #rape #victim #protest #march #losangeles #pride #amberrose #courage #lalife #change #scotus #justice #women #standup #metoo #timesup #consent #women #justice #standup

text:
villa hantu di pantai setangi, lombok utara ini bagus sekali. 
sayang tak sudah karena izin pembangunan tak ada atau belum ada katanya. 
orang asing yang membangun sudah tak ada. 
meninggal dunia. 
tinggalkan villa yang pemandangan laut dan sayup gunung agung sore hari bukan main bagus. 
ngopi dan pisang goreng bisa diorder dari warung pinggir jalan. 
juga ada ikan bakar atau jagung. 
relax and enjoy your cup of coffee or tea. 
setelah gempa dan berita palsu tsunami berlalu, aku lihat orang ingin melihat mulai ada. 
semoga hantu penghuni masih disitu. 
apalah arti villa hantu tanpa hantu?

brett kavanaugh should be sitting before a confirmation board on tuesday october 2, 2018, but of course one republican, not up for re-election jeff flake (r-az), has decided to live up to his name and flake by offering to vote  in favor of moving kavanaugh to the confirmation vote on the condition that the fbi be allowed to conduct an investigation into already investigated matters. president trump authorized the investigation on the basis that it would be limited in scope and time. specifically, they are only authorized to investigate “credible accusations,” and being that there are none, i have to assume christine ford’s accusation alone will be the focus of this investigation. additionally they have “less than a week” to conclude the investigation. so between 1-6 days.  almost immediately after it was announced that the investigation had been green-lit, christine ford’s lawyers issued a statement saying that they were pleased that the republicans has the spinal fortitude of a jelly fish and would be happy to further exploit that fact, and more or less demanded that the fbi scope and time limitation be changed to unlimited.  we never should have made it to this point. these delays are ridiculous, sign this petition, tell the senate to end this madness, stop the delays, stop dragging a good man’s name through the mud, finish this investigation and get to the vote no later than october 4, 2018. click on the link in my bio to sign the petition to confirm brett kavanaugh!

text:
this situation is creating a lot of trauma for a lot of women. i’ve seen so many people ask why women do not come forward earlier, as if they’re holding back that juicy little nugget for an opportunistic time. that is not the case at all. i think women do not come forward because it’s not worth the trauma of it’s his word against mine; they’re not as emotional strong as other women who report these incidents at the time of the occurrence; maybe those women had a friend who encouraged them to report it & supported them along the way; maybe we do not feel like we matter enough to come forward; if friends saw this happened & didn’t stop it then maybe the victim does not feel important enough to come forward. there are lots of reasons.

if you have not been a victim of sexual assault, then you probably shouldn’t comment on it.

there’s no way you’re ever going to be able to relate.

my government is failing me. it’s failing so many women. #metoo is far reaching. it’s not just in hollywood, it’s in wichita. it’s at college. it’s in high school. it’s at your neighbors house.

you have no fucking idea how big #metoo is.

text:
as crazy as this may sound, this is actually not impossible. while there may be 9 supreme court justices now, the constitution does not specify how many justices can serve at a time. that's up to congress. in fact, when the court first began in 1789, there were only 6 justices on the bench. then there were 7, and as many as 10. the numbers have fluctuated over the years. constitutionally, there is no minimum or maximum number of justices that can serve on the court.

text:
dear dr. christine blasey ford,
your face inspires me with its strength, courage, pain, and honesty. i rarely post a work in progress, but this piece, in its current unfinished state, is a powerful analogy for the status of women today. as i add colour and definition to your image, so to do women increase their visibility every day. truth will set us free.  we have strength in numbers. i will finish this painting next week, and celebrate the senate doing the right thing. the only thing. your bravery is beautiful. on behalf on women and men everywhere, i believe.  oil on canvas. 5ft x 3.5 ft. wip.  #purpleglassesfordrchristineblaseyford #ibelievedrchristineblaseyford #lindseygraham #kavanaughhearing #stopkavanaugh #huffingtonpost #notantimanjustprowoman #notantimanjustantidisgustingbehavior #notantimanjustprojustice #ibelieveher #ibelieve #metoo

text:
don’t think these are the right words,
but they are the only ones i could find.
i read a post that said,
imagine you were ford and u see the person who sexually assaulted u, riding to a place of power where they will be able to dictate the rights of your body, and other women’s bodies... that’s where it gets me... i’m not political... but, unfortunately, i think there are a lot of us who know what is like to not have control over what is happening to your body... it’s, terrifying. 
i know some horror stories and my heart races when i think about some of these ppls predicaments and how they were able to face them.
every story, every detail of it- every arrangement of words, every little part of each of our stories- is different.
and there are often chapters none of us read aloud and hope we will never have to. 
i hope you never have to read a story aloud that you don’t want to recall
-
-

text_retweet:
#repost @rachaelmaddox with @get_repost
・・・
hold your beloved. close and with care.
 rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth in speed and texture, poetry and metaphor.

ask her, how old do you feel, just right here, just right now? ask her, what does that part of you need to know, need to hear? ask her, how can i help you experience repair? – even if i wasn't the one who caused the pain. – even if i accidentally piled more on.

give her space and presence and care, so much care, until something exhales from the center of her pain. (non-poetically, let there be quiet and breathing and no words.

in the absence of your knowing what's going on for her, everything is coming together under her skin.) hold your beloved like the god of redemption is sending light through your willing hands, your steady chest, your loving eyes.

hold your beloved and let her cry and cry and cry

without needing to know why.

if you stay there, dear and willing, she will tell you everything, and you will believe her.

then, in your anger, in your concern, in your fear, you might feel the instinct to ask her if she could've done something differently.

not had those drinks. not smoked that pot. not gone out looking for love or lust or good conversation.

not gotten a job. not gone to the party. not had a god forsaken female body.

tonight, i beg of you – ask a different question:

what's going on with the men? 
you might want to ask, have you ever thought about reporting him?

and mostly, she'll say no. or yes, but... sometimes, she'll tell you how horrible it was.

tonight, i beg of you – ask a different question:

how can i support you? 
hold your beloved. close and with care. rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth.

this is the first, most important thing you can do.

then tomorrow, put your own two hands on your very own heart and ask the god within, "where should i begin? use me move me make me a force for healing justice protection love." listen. listen. listen.

we needs your hands and your heart, your devotion to doing your part.

i know you want to. i know the king in there is in despair. the real repair is rising.

#metoo #healinghappens #rebloomtogether #love

text:
me too:
i was raped for the first time at a cycling team training camp in california. i was told to basically keep riding and not talk about it. it was awful. it made me start hating racing. it made me weird about sex and hate my body. i still have a hard time speaking about it..... and this was only the first time something like this happened to me. 
we have to believe each other and listen to each other and see each other. sexual assault is not a joke and fuck all men’s “man card.” we are not seperate. we are connected. imagine your daughter or your mother experiencing a man shoving their penis into their vagina or mouth. imagine how bad it hurts spiritually, mentally and physically. then please sit with that before you say anything regarding anything to do with this situation. #metoo

text: this a lengthy read, be warned. in light of recent events, i’m appalled at some of the people in my life. honestly, i don’t even care what side of this kavanaugh, cosby, turner, or any other controversy you’re on. but watch what you say about rape survivors. growing up i’ve heard countless of people around me talk down on rape victims. saying they must’ve been wearing provocative clothing, must’ve had too much to drink, or the dreaded “they’re lying, they weren’t raped”. there are many reasons rapes go unreported. lack of proof, being threatened, feeling shame, the abuser has a powerful position in the community, so many reasons. i never thought i could come forward with my story. i thought i’d be talked down on by my own family and friends because of what they say about rape. people ask us to feel bad for the rapist? because their image is ruined? fuck off for even wanting me to feel remorse for any abuser. they knew what they were doing and they need to punished. i encourage everyone to watch what you say about rape victims, you never know who around you is dealing with their own battles. that little girl who’s listening to what you have to say should never have to grow up scared to come forward because she feels the people around her will judge her. today isn’t my day to share my story. it doesn’t matter when my day is, my day will be my day. in ten years if i decide it’s my day, it doesn’t make it any less true than if i had told it the day after it happened, because it still happened. don’t underestimate the power of your words, and look out for those around you. and to my fellow survivors, you’re the strongest people i know✊🏼 #metoo

text:
this week has been very challenging for me. #drchristineblaseyford bravery has given me the strength to share my story. in my early 20’s, i was the victim of sexual assault by someone i trusted. i don’t want to go into the details. 
i decided to report it and pursue justice (how young and naive i was). i filed a police report and few days later, the detective assigned to my case picked me up at my office and took me to the police station where i shared the series of events that took place. the detective got emotional and said he had a daughter my age. he warned me that they see many cases, and they can result in a long and challenging process that may not turn out in my favor due to the fact i knew this person. i appreciated the warning but i told him i wanted to press charges anyway. i walked into the police station that day as joan of arc on a crusade but i left alone on the bus, feeling humiliated and powerless. the da later decided to dismiss the case even though there was evidence, citing the number of violent crimes cases they had at their office. 
the positive from this story: i got a restraining order and legal support from a group of female lawyers, working pro bono for women in need of help and protection. i love these attorneys. my family and friends also really stepped up and helped me. i will never forget the messages of love and support i received, especially those from my male friends. 
even though it’s hard to share this trauma, it’s even harder to imagine what dr. ford is going through. i feel obligated to try to change the narrative from one of shame to one of courage and triumph. i don’t need to keep this a secret - i was a victim.

i’m not the only woman. in fact:
▪️every 98 secs an american is sexually assaulted
▪️1 of every 6 american women has been the victim of attempted or completed rape.
▪️ 6 of every 1,000 rapists will be charged 
i hope this week sheds light on the traumatic process why more women don’t come forward. i wish i could go back to the young brave girl that believed in justice. i hope we can create a society where other women feel safe to share their stories. #metoo #survivor #believesurvivors #drford #victimshaming
name: Sara Ruffin 🧘‍♀️
tweet_full:
this week has been very challenging for me. #drchristineblaseyford bravery has given me the strength to share my story. in my early 20’s, i was the victim of sexual assault by someone i trusted. i don’t want to go into the details. 
i decided to report it and pursue justice (how young and naive i was). i filed a police report and few days later, the detective assigned to my case picked me up at my office and took me to the police station where i shared the series of events that took place. the detective got emotional and said he had a daughter my age. he warned me that they see many cases, and they can result in a long and challenging process that may not turn out in my favor due to the fact i knew this person. i appreciated the warning but i told him i wanted to press charges anyway. i walked into the police station that day as joan of arc on a crusade but i left alone on the bus, feeling humiliated and powerless. the da later decided to dismiss the case even though there was evidence, citing the number of violent crimes cases they had at their office. 
the positive from this story: i got a restraining order and legal support from a group of female lawyers, working pro bono for women in need of help and protection. i love these attorneys. my family and friends also really stepped up and helped me. i will never forget the messages of love and support i received, especially those from my male friends. 
even though it’s hard to share this trauma, it’s even harder to imagine what dr. ford is going through. i feel obligated to try to change the narrative from one of shame to one of courage and triumph. i don’t need to keep this a secret - i was a victim.

i’m not the only woman. in fact:
▪️every 98 secs an american is sexually assaulted
▪️1 of every 6 american women has been the victim of attempted or completed rape.
▪️ 6 of every 1,000 rapists will be charged 
i hope this week sheds light on the traumatic process why more women don’t come forward. i wish i could go back to the young brave girl that believed in justice. i hope we can create a society where other women feel safe to share their stories. #metoo #survivor #believesurvivors #drford #victimshaming

text:
uhm hmm.. yep.. and this 🤔🤔 (pause)

i was raped once. i was silent. i was scared. i was experiencing (what i now know *unneeded*) self blame. and why did i not report? by the time i sorted my feelings with multiple counselors.. he died. he was dead.

is that any reason for me not to speak out now? he died, so it “must be over”? it’ll never be over for me. i cannot remember the date, the time.. but i remember the face. i remember the fear. and worst of all— i remember being made fun of the morning after.

before yesterday, i didn’t give a bother about anyone knowing (minus a small few who recently found out). it was my business. but i sat silent, scrolling through my newsfeed, just disgusted.

i thank god every single day that my mother brought me into this world with so much love that she recognized she was not capable of giving a tiny child the life that they deserved at that moment in time. i thank god her family was more than supportive. i thank god i was adopted into a family that was tasked not only by my entire birth family, but by god himself in raising me. and i thank god that i have been luckier than so many more people because of all that love. but i question god because of what happened that night.

you know what fucks me up most about this whole thing? it’s not that i have developed triggers.. not that i have since been on anxiety medication.. not that i often have to see someone about my nightmares.. what really fucks me up is that writing this post will most likely be more controversial than it will be helpful, or raw. what fucks me up is that no matter what you say, or what you think, or what you believe, or what you preach.. i will still have that anxiety, those nightmares, that remembrance of the fear. he’s dead, but i’ll never be healed. #metoo #whyididntreport

text:
i am the mother of one of the most privileged people on the planet: a white male. when i was young i rarely thought about having children, and when i did, i always imagined having daughters. when i found out i was pregnant with a boy i was excited but uncertain, thinking, “i don’t know anything about boys!” but this was untrue. i knew how boys had made me feel uncomfortable about my body as early as elementary school, how men had scared me on the street in high school, and how male students were patronizing toward me in college. i knew how so many interactions have impacted my life and who i am today.

my son is compassionate, goofy, and smart. he is the love of my life. but i do not forget that one day my sweet toddler could become that catcalling teenager, that patronizing classmate, or even a predator. 
so as he sleeps his sweet toddler sleep in his warm, safe bed, i make him (and everyone he meets) a promise: 
to give him space to be sad and scared, and not just commend his bravery and strength.

to encourage him to be courteous to all, rather than chivalrous toward women.

to teach him that men can be nurturing, warm, sensitive, beautiful, and vulnerable. 
to explain that he has incredible privilege in this world, and he can use it to stand up for and empower others. 
i will work hard to let him know that he can both wonder at the size of trucks and appreciate the beauty of flowers. 
that being called “girly” is not an insult. 
that he can come to me without fear when he makes mistakes. 
that i will take time to listen to him, and to answer awkward questions honestly. 
avi, i promise i will do my absolute best to raise you to be someone who gives a damn. to not just believe in people and their stories, but to care.

text:
i #believe survivors because i am one.
.
the news has been hard to hear the past week as people openly post their opinions and judgements on a situation that they have no idea about.
.
this is not the time or place where i tell my story. that story and experience is mine and i will share when i feel empowered to do so. #metoo but #nottoday
.
you do not have the right or power to shame someone who holds on to a secret for 20 years. some people take those stories and experiences to their grave and carry it alone in their hearts forever.
.
if someone chooses to tell how they were victimized, whether they do so 5 minutes, 5 years, or 5 decades after it happened, they still deserve to be heard, believed, and supported.
.
we live in a society and justice system where so often the abuser is protected and the victim is shamed, made to feel at fault, and silenced.
.
to the women who are choosing to stand up and speak their truth, even when there's fear, you make me proud. you are brave and your story will be a part of the change. thank you for fighting for us all.
.
to the women who have buried their pain and truth, too afraid or ashamed or broken to utter the words... you too are brave. i am proud of you too.
we are fighting for you too.
.
i see you, i hear you, i believe you, and i love you. .
.
#ibelieveyou #ibelieve #empowered #iseeyou #ihearyou #speakyourtruth #truth #powertothevictim #womensupportwomen #metoomovement #drford #bethechange

let's talk numbers here. i don't normally involve myself in politics, and especially not on a business focused venue, but this hits close to my soul because i am a #survivor. 🙇‍♀️
1 in 6 women will be the victim in a rape or attempted rape in her life. 1 in 6. that means someone (maybe more than 1) in your family is a victim of rape. 💖💖💖💖💖💔
every 96 seconds, there is another sexual assault in america. in the time it takes me to type this...another sexual assault has happened. 🇺🇸
individuals in the 18-24 years age range are 92% more likely to be raped or assaulted than those over 65.
👧>👵
students are at a higher risk of sexual abuse or assault than non students, and that statistic carries through all genders, and is exacerbated for transgender students.
👩‍🎓👨‍🎓
94% of women who are raped will experience some form of ptsd.
🧠
7 out of 10 rapes are committed by individuals known personally by the victim. 🧑👩👩‍🏫👩‍🌾👩‍🔧 when i reported my multiple cases of sexual assault by a family member, my claims were turned on me, and i was punished for slandering my 85 yr old grandfather. i was 7. 
#whyididntreport #stopvictimblaming #metoo #ptsd #rape #sexualassault #molestation #woman #stronger #survivor #resist #politicalpartiesdontmatter #actionmatters

text:
in the past two weeks i've been having anxiety attacks. cosby, #metoo, then the recent hearings ... have brought me to tears. for the women involved and yes, for myself.
🔸
ten years ago i was raped. i didn't report.
🔹
i didn’t report because by then i had gone through three hospitalizations. i would be labeled crazy and unreliable.
🔸
i didn’t report because my gynecologist, who extricated the tampon that had been shoved up inside me (only discovered a week later) told me it would be difficult to prove.
🔹
i didn't report because i was afraid i would break and make another suicide attempt. (the day of my rape i felt proud for feeling comfortable to socialize again 2 years after an abusive and isolating relationship.)
🔸
three months later, i went to the police station. i waited an hour for female police officers to arrive. i shared everything ... but his name. i was afraid. he was rich and socially connected (as my ex had been). i feared i'd be decimated on the stand.
🔹
i saw my rapist at parties. i’d hold my breath and wait until i got into my car to scream.
🔸
five months later i was told that it would be difficult to prosecute. as someone who always looked out for others i felt selfish. i felt helpless and hopeless. i attempted suicide, succumbing to the relief from the pain of being voiceless.
🔹
i eventually learned there were others. one woman who got away privately contacted me.
🔹
i live with my decision every day. the pain dulls but forever lingers.
🔸
to anyone who wonders why dr. #christineblaseyford might have finally came out as #kavanough came close to confirmation ... imagine seeing your attacker in the news on a regular basis. having to relive trauma on a repeat cycle. being reminded that his life went on and some days, many years later, you can still feel like the attack happened just yesterday. the sense of urgency takes over.
🔹
it's a far different culture than it was 10 years ago. i pray that brave women such as dr. ford can provide hope for others to share their stories and, perhaps in such a supportive environment, report crimes for which there must never be any level of shame.
.
#whyididntreport #suicidesurvivor #ramblinrosé

text:
@calgaryherald you published an editorial promoting the concept that people should not be held accountable for their former actions. sexual assault, misogyny or rape should not even be a controversial topic.

this has effectively broke all ethical and moral responsibilities the world of journalism could possibly claim. freedom of press vs misuse of press. know the difference. the media has a huge influence on forming and informing news and views and must promote greater objectivity than this.

you have used your influence to publish vitriolic content, and then subsequently censoring people who do not agree with your views. 
shame on you for publishing an article so insensitive to the victims of sexual assault. there should be consequences for rapists. what they do, and how they treat people,  matters. they might think it’s “irrelevant” to whom they are now but it’s changed the lives of their victims forever.

trauma no matter the place, circumstances or gender follows a victim - having lasting and detrimental impacts. survivors don’t have a time limit for their suffering. 
sexual assault is not a joke, not a punchline and not a tool to sell your product. 
i can’t believe you represent my city as a news outlet. 
i am watching tv right now and i am incredibly appalled. how are we supposed to raise our children and teach them values of respect, compassion, and equality?? seeing a bunch of white, privileges males acknowledge a victims trauma, yet publicly dismiss it with disbelief...if we can’t push back voting to investigate this, what are we teaching our children?? whenever something like this hits the news, it makes me relive my own experience. i was six. he was my babysitter. my brain remembers bits and pieces of the trauma. i survived. i am a survivor.

@iamhertribe what you posted today moved me and i couldn’t have said it better myself: “just as dr.ford and countless other women, my truth does not need permission to exist here, and it surely doesn’t need to tip-toe around political talk for your comfort. it took me a long time to find my voice and it’s only going to get louder. i will risk feeling humiliated to stand up for what i believe in”

text:
i just... have no words today, but thankfully these badass witches do 🖤
.
addendum (some words): quick tip to use on anyone that might say (and i’ve heard this too much lately) that a person (kavanaugh) shouldn’t be denied a job (supreme court judge) based on their actions (sexual assault) from decades ago (high school). while it is true that this brutal, misogynistic behavior used to be more accepted, more the norm, that womxn & femmes & any other victims of sexual violence had to deal with in silence, may we remind you, those times are gone. it is no longer acceptable under any circumstances.
.
so may i suggest that persons seeking powerful positions involving truth and justice look elsewhere for employment. perhaps employment that allows you to make reparations for your horrendous deeds, if not in a legal context, then at least in a personal, social, or political context. it’s really the least you could do. and you would be lucky to have the opportunity. so scrutinize your past, and i dunno, make sure you never sexually assaulted anyone. it’s not hard.
.
#femininerising #femmefury #ibelieveher #shedoes #metoo #blacklivesmatter #translivesmatter #everyonebutthepatriarchy #timesup

text:
recently i have been avoiding posting photographs of my altar. honestly, i’ve been avoiding posting in general. i am a bit overwhelmed by the discussions regarding sexual assault that are going around. but this ends now.
⠀⠀ sexual assault, rape, molestation, abuse... the air is thick with the worst words. all of which i still pick shards of out of my own body on a regular basis. all of which i have experienced and attempted to move through and beyond and every single one i have received minimal support about from my blood relatives. i choose to make my own family, to surround myself and surrender to the love of those who truly see me.
⠀⠀ angry doesn’t begin to describe this feeling. i am shattered, have been shattered, and will be shattered. again and again i will have to remember the things that have been done to me beyond my consent. and i burn those memories regularly. i eat the ash of them and then stand up straight to continue pushing forward. but this month has been hard. photographs, names, instigation, lack of consciousness, a lack of support, no energetic exchange, no concept or care for how much these things weight me down.
⠀⠀ i am finished. i lay it all at the feet of my goddess, at the feet of ishtar, queen of heaven, sacred whore and divine lady. she who shed and walked through hell to claim what was hers by rights. she who laid waste to cities for simple disrespect. mother and warrior.
⠀⠀ there is no more room within me for sorrow. i can’t keep space for this pain anymore. those who abuse us shall be like worms, so that we may smash them beneath our highly-arched feet.
⠀⠀ i name you, uncle, boyfriend, neighbor, colleague, friend, every person who ever took from me. i draw it all back inward now. there is no more space within me for you.
•••

text: i have been in a weird headspace for days. i've been watching this investigation and the hearings and never thought about how it would, for the first time since the #metoo movement took the media by storm, be triggering. i'm jumpy and anxious. i can feel my ptsd clawing at the back of my brain, but i'm so desperate to know if #drford will be believed, so desperate for the hope that finally women, like me, will be heard and respected. i don't know if it's better for my mental health to ignore it so i can avoid a daily trigger, or simply muscle through in the hopes that i can watch this pivotal moment unfold.

text:
🇺🇸 lindsey graham for the win! rightly so. news articles are saying that the fact ford's  witnesses couldn't recall the event doesn't mean kavanaugh is innocent. really? i thought he was "innocent" until proved guilty.  we aren't looking for evidence that he's innocent, that's automatic. we are looking for evidence of guilt! i watched both give their statements, and their treatment of him and his accuser, ford, were noticeably different. then he his mocked by his defensive stance while defending himself and his family from an accusation with from what i understand, no credible evidence from ford, or her witnesses. 
this mans family is being threatened, and you expect him not to show human emotion? i could have cared less about this a week ago, but after what i have watched... it's ridiculous. 
he has been backed and supported by women that he has known since the age of 14, and had nothing but an outstanding record, according to these people... but it is tarnished because he drank beer in high school and college, like most us...and that's what makes him guilty? he has played his hand and they know his defense. they'll use it against him in the next week, and bring more accusations against him that follow his calender schedule, since they know that's a pretty solid piece of evidence.

due process is still a thing. innocent until proven guilty, not the other way around. like kavanaugh stated, accusations should be taken serious and given a fair process... but this is not what is taking place. especially when women were claiming guilt before hearing any defending statement. this causes not only ford to receive threats, but also kavanaugh and his family. 
it's sick! 🇺🇸 .
.

text_retweet: brett kavanaugh is the symptom. rape culture and patriarchy is the disease. same with trump. same with the rapists outted by the #metoo movement (not to mention white supremacy, capitalism, etc). men, if you actually care...listen to women, and the women on the front lines of the anti-sexist, anti-rape culture, feminist movement and get to work. and if you’re a man, wondering if i’m talking about you, i can assure you that i am. you need to be a man that other men know stands against rape culture. that other men know won’t let this shit slide. that other men can come to you with their questions about what to do to be a part of the solution. we all have circles of influence, and we need to influence them. we don’t deserve credit for not being a kavanaugh, a trump, or a weinstein. the only way to change this world to make it safer for women and girls is to be preemptive and do the shit that you see almost no other men doing. when you see lots of women in your life re-posting an article or a meme about rape culture, but not men doing it, you do it. violence against women is *men’s* violence against women over 99% of the time. this is our job to fix. guys, next time you hear liberal men complaining about kavanaugh, ask “what are you doing to end rape culture?” ・・・ #repost @mattmcgorry with @get_repost #stopkavanaugh #believesurvivors #believewomen

text:
i believe the personal is political. cynics assert that dr. cristine blasey ford, like dr. anita hill before her, has chosen to speak of her experience of trauma for political reasons in the sense of having a partisan goal. but the struggle playing out in washington that has the attention of the world is political because it’s brought to light the deeply personal issues of power and abuse: power as the ability to compel someone with less power to do your bidding, even when it comes with great harm to the party being compelled. 
the testimony and the surrounding discussions online of experiences of abuse and violence have highlighted the stark divisions in society that keep some in power perpetually at the cost of having to dehumanize their targets, divisions marked by gender, race, sexuality, economics and beliefs.  reading so many brave accounts of sharing painful experiences of trauma also acts as a reminder of the importance of self care and support. 
please, reach out to available supports to talk including the national sexual assault hotline at 800-656-hope (4673) or the safe helpline at 877-995-5247 #believesurvivors #believewomen #whyididntreport #metoo #endsexualassault #mentalhealth #trauma #fearlessfriday

text: i’ve always been so scared to share my story, but these past two days have been extra hard. i am so in awe of dr ford and her courage in telling the entire nation about the worst night of her life, and i hope to one day be that strong. i, too, was sexually assaulted by a peer when i was younger, in the 7th grade. i, too, was too scared to say anything right away, fearing consequences and pretending it wasn’t as bad as i thought it was. until it happened again. and again. i have barely told anyone these truths. for years i was so broken, and had to learn how to forgive someone who was never sorry. someone who never faced consequences outside school because his family thought he did nothing wrong. someone who would walk past me every day in high school and pretend like nothing happened. it still hurt. i’m so sorry that so many of you knew him, were friends with him, or trusted him, yet i never warned you of what he’s done. i’m so sorry i protected him for so long, because i didn’t want to ruin his life, even though he already destroyed part of mine. i know better now, and i refuse to let him determine my narrative. instead i spread joy, show grace, and strive to radiate goodness, because i am so much better than what he made of me. i have family and friends who support me and a god who will never let me down. so, thank you, dr ford, for being so strong and voicing the pain of so many in this country. thank you for representing us. thank you for showing that we have stories, and that we will not be afraid. thank you for giving me a voice to fight back. thank you for giving me hope. no matter what happens this week, thank you. so much. #metoo

text:
believe her
... dear broken rose,
you are more than your physical form. 
you are more than an accumulation of experiences, 
more than woman,
more than man. 
and so no label can define you completely, 
no box can hold you eternally, 
no person can break you.

the broken rose uploads to the ether,
drifts in the expansive waters of
renewal, expansive love, and chaos too.
we sync and sink. breaking completely, wholly.
such is the power of the broken rose.
the first crack was merely a reminder that 
you are more than petals and rose leaf, 
more than hip and stem.
the night sky wraps around you 
like a heavy weighted blanket, 
absolving earthly woes.
and when it's ready,
a call let out by the soul, silent yet traveling 
great distances through time and space, 
brings the rose,
peice by peice, 
together again.
and you can laugh because part of you knew,
you where your own salvation.
... i am also a survivor ✊

this broken rose is for dr.ford, 
it's for the millions -billions- of survivors world wide, and it is for me. 
#metoo #believeher  #photomanipulation #art #awareness #artistsofinstagram #poster #glitch #rose #poetry

text:
trigger warning: sexual assault, rape/culture
.
sexual assault has been a topic of interest due to recent events. one issue that coincides with assault is how victims are being treated. often times friends try to console and care, but sometimes it can be harsh. i read countless articles that give a good list of excellent ways to help those who have been a victim of sexual assault.
.
.
1. listen-often times victims just need someone that will hear them out and listen without judgement. listen without waiting to respond.
. 
2. remind them that it's not their fault-no one ever deserves this or asks for this. no victim has wanted to be in this position.
.
3. ask questions in a sensitive way-avoid using why questions, they sound judgemental.
.
4. honor your friends autonomy-this is so important. do not ever force someone to report their assault. do not threaten to tell their loved ones. respect their decision. they will be ready when they feel they are. not when you are. i understand it can be frustrating to hear events such as these that happen to your friend and this may seem like a good idea. just know it is never a good idea. be patient with them.
.
5. understand that a survivors responded are varied and complex-every victim experiences assault in different ways, so don't make them feel like their experience was any less than what it was.
.
6. help to establish safety-make them feel safe around you. they already told you something personal. don't break the trust they already have for you.
.
7. offer resources-this speaks for itself.
.
8. take care of yourself-while it's nice to be there for a victim, it can take a toll on you as well. i've always been an advocate of self-care. so do what you need to do to take care of yourself during all this.
.
i know this is long, but it is necessary with how often this happens. if you still aren't sure how to handle this kind of situation, research it. they're already going through enough so just remember to be sensitive and be patient.
#rape #sexualassault #rape #rapeculture #howto #howtohelp #victimofsexualassault #metoo #daterape #title9 #triggerwarning

trigger warning: sexual assault, rape/culture
.
sexual assault has been a topic of interest due to recent events. one issue that coincides with assault is how victims are being treated. often times friends try to console and care, but sometimes it can be harsh. i read countless aicles that give a good list of excellent ways to help those who have been a victim of sexual assault.
.
.
1. listen-often times victims just need someone that will hear them out and listen without judgement. listen without waiting to respond.
. 
2. remind them that it is not their fault-no one ever deserves this or asks for this. no victim has wanted to be in this position.
.
3. ask questions in a sensitive way-avoid using why questions, they sound judgemental.
.
4. honor your friends autonomy-this is so impoant. do not ever force someone to repo their assault. do not threaten to tell their loved ones. respect their decision. they will be ready when they feel they are. not when you are. i understand it can be frustrating to hear events such as these that happen to your friend and this may seem like a good idea. just know it is never a good idea. be patient with them.
.
5. understand that a survivors responded are varied and complex-every victim experiences assault in different ways, so do not make them feel like their experience was any less than what it was.
.
6. help to establish safety-make them feel safe around you. they already told you something personal. do not break the trust they already have for you.
.
7. offer resources-this speaks for itself.
.
8. take care of yourself-while it is nice to be there for a victim, it can take a toll on you as well. i have always been an advocate of self-care. so do what you need to do to take care of yourself during all this.
.
i know this is long, but it is necessary with how often this happens. if you still are not sure how to handle this kind of situation, research it. they're already going through enough so just remember to be sensitive and be patient.

text: i’ve been seeing a lot of my friends come forward with their #metoo stories and it’s helped me feel more comfortable with mine. about two months ago i was raped. it was one of the most traumatic experiences of my life. i started drinking excessively and taking opiates to block out my intense flashbacks. i was admitted to a hospital to help intervene my risky behavior. i felt worthless and hopeless. my body has finally healed, but that’s the easiest part of this recovery. it still feels like it happened yesterday, and i haven’t even begun to heal my brain. i’ve quit my job and i’m drowning in schoolwork. i’m always afraid of what each hour will bring with my mood swings and flashbacks. with the recent events on tv, i’ve felt like completely isolating myself, but i don’t. i can’t. i have to keep pressing onward. i keep studying, socializing, and breathing not because i want to, but because i need to. the old, passive lisa is gradually fading out and it’s being replaced by this rough around the edges fighter, survivor. the transition is painful, but one day i’ll wake up and realize how far i’ve come from this point in my life and i’ll be proud of me again. until then, i’ll fight for another day.

text: i went for a late afternoon run today and ran my longest distance yet. that was definitely a victory, and the gorgeous sunset views made it all the more wonderful. the thing is, i couldn't stop thinking about dr. blasey-ford and the bravery of all the women, including the #sheroes who confronted senator flake today, who are sharing their stories.the real  victory tonight was in d.c.! as i went for my run, i chose my route through prospect park carefully and made sure, as i always do, not to take the lovely, but less populated paths, and instead stayed on the main road. as the sun began to set, i was also very aware that i should head home quickly, so i would not be in the park, alone, after dark. thank you, thank you to everyone speaking out and fighting for a better world! this is all very hard, but, my hope is it will also be healing for us, individually, and collectively. #believesurvivors #abetterworldispossible #nevergiveup #activismworks #everyvoicematters #metoo #timesup #strongertogether #fiercefemales #womeninspiringwomen #stayhopeful #fightforit #runnermom #couchto5k #runnerintraining #brooklynlife #brooklynphotography #momofteens #prospectpark #fitmomsofig #onlyonebody #fitnessjourney #mindbodyconnection #takingchargeofmybody #choosehealth #ificandoityoucantoo

text:
we are survivors
we have been hurt 
betrayed, ignored,
degraded and dehumanized
at times,
afraid we will never be whole again
yet we persevere. 
taught we should have given 
what had been taken
we struggle with questioning,
our identity, society, and 
at times, even family.
but we are valid,
and we will learn that.
we are survivors.

text:
“embrace all of your feelings”. this phrase has been coming up for me these last few days.  and then i captured this picture of my sweet kitty, chloe.  she reminds me that even our shadow sides are beautiful.  shining the light of investigation on all of my traumas, fears, feelings and thoughts is worth the freedom it ignites.  seeing and saying our pain takes the power out of it.  the last few days have been hard to watch, but in seeing so many share their truth, i see the release of shame and pain.  we are healing on a massive scale.  when we truly see each other, we all heal.  we are guided; we are good.  we are all children of god.
#collective #healing #peace #metoo #change #childofgod #seen #heard #loved #womenempowerment #believesurvivors #compassion #all #one

text:
i believe survivors. i believe anita hill. i believe dr. blasey ford. i believe we, as a people, can do better. i believe we can see people in their humanity rather than as property, conquests, or simply objects for the taking. 
yes, masculinity fundamentally needs to shift. to find a definition better than dominance. and, at the same time, this narrative of dominance shows up across the gender spectrum. 
i was raped as a teen by a girl older than me. i was so ashamed, for so many reasons. largely, because i was taught that women can’t and don’t rape. i thought people wouldn’t believe me or that i should be embarrassed that it didn’t happen at a mans hands. worst of all, i was afraid everyone would know i was gay if they found out. 
over a decade later, i learned that my story is common in the queer community. that often, many of our first queer experiences involve the same dominance and toxicity of our straight counterparts. 
years ago i made it a goal to be open about being a survivor, and i am in my friendships and in poetry. and still, i still grapple with shame and triggers. i ask us all to consider the relationship between masculinity and homophobia and how this narrative came to be common.
im not sure how to end this post,. my hope is that we all can move towards a culture of affirmative consent, that sex is only sexy when consensual, and that sexual predators don’t exist anymore. one step at a time, hey? #whyididntreport #ibelieveher #believesurvivors #metoo #healing #queerlove #queerfam

text:
with everything that has been going on recently i feel compelled to share again. and this is not political for me.. my point here is that it is not ok to make jokes about rape/sexual assault/sexual abuse. no matter the circumstances!!! i am a sexual abuse survivor and every time i see a joke, or a comment about how ‘we women’ make this shit up for attention or money....it literally makes me ill. i have flash backs. it breaks my heart. i question my worth. my ability as a wife and mother. i start believing the untrue things these people are saying about us survivors. 
i didn’t choose what happened to me when i was a child, but i suffer in ways most people cannot imagine. i live with that trauma every day, and it enrages me to see people joking about it. i’ve worked extremely hard to overcome my childhood trauma, so next time you want to make a joke, or you think one is funny. think about me, and the childhood i had robbed away at roughly 4yrs old and again at 7yrs old and again at 13yrs old, because i didn’t have a voice, at least not one that people heard.

i have a voice now. and i’m loud and very clear about this topic. if you don’t like it - that’s totally fine, and i can respect that. but please just do the same, have some respect... #survivor #imwithher #imwithhim #imwithyou #ibelieveher #standup #speakup #warrior #sexualabusesurvivor #metoo #bethechange #motherhoodrising #birthofmama #nomore1in4 #nomore1in6 #theyouniquefoundation #thehavenretreat #bebrave #timesup #motherhoodunplugged #worthy

text: i’m back on the grid after a week out of town and 5 days meditating in a tipi.  majority of the rich white men in power are still predictably💩and i’m still predictably a wild feminist and hot dayuuuuum dr. blasey ford is fierce.  it boggles my mind a bit how anyone in this day and age can wonder why a person might not come forward with allegations of sexual assault/abuse/misconduct.  and here this woman is standing up to one of the most established “good ole boy clubs” in the world.  i hope she feels us supporting her, believing her. 💛⚡️✨✊🏽💛 hold my hands sisters (and feminist brothers) we gotta do this together; it’s time to topple the patriarchy.  loving all of you as watching/listening to the utter ignorance (and sometimes straight up dumbassery) around this pours salt (or much worse) in our wounds.  #webelievesurvivors #ibelieveher #believewomen #juntos #together #united #sisterhoodwillsaveus #fighttheman #riseup #flourish #healing #wildfeminist #imnotafraidtooffendyou #speaktruthtopower #questionauthority #metoo #ustoo #dangerousnastywildsmartwoman⚡️🔥🌜💛✊🏽✊🏽✊🏽💛🌙💥⚡️ (photo jungalow)

text_retweet:
“there is a pivotal juncture in every heroine’s journey when she stands alone. she is led by the depth of her convictions to take a stand, to name the unaddressed, to call out of hiding the secret malaise in her community. she arrives at a standpoint not without doubts, but in spite of them. and sometimes there is a hefty price to pay, like being the target of criticism, or worse, rejection from the group which is at odds with her truth.
.
the dissenting voice speaks for the voiceless. and in some ironic plot twist, it is in the revolt against false belonging that real solidarity can be born. your willingness to speak the truth about something that disagrees with you is what allows for the undamming of communication, giving all involved a fertile place to grow and the chance to build a real village.”
.
excerpt from
belonging: remembering ourselves home by
toko-pa turner (belongingbook.com)
.
artwork by @onbeinginyourbody
.

text:
it isn’t always easy for the rainbow to arrive in all its beauty and magic. sometimes, it comes out of dark storm clouds and looks broken up a bit on its way down but the illumination of that spectrum of light still stops us in our tracks and turns our eyes upward. we pause to appreciate what has found its way to us - this illustration of the myriad ways light refracts at different angles.
i keep holding tight to the hope that we are this rainbow ... fighting our way free and showing up, shining brightly, insisting on dazzling the world with our simply extraordinary selves.

#rainbowconnection #believesurvivors #ibelieveher #metoo #timesup

text:
as we witness history being made, we must never forget the women who have gone before...
.
we inherit you. your skin, your eyes, the way you looked at the world. the way the world looked at you.
.

we inherit your fear of touch. your fear of being struck down. your fear of being found out. of being caught.
.

we too know this fear. it is ours and it is yours. we know the danger that awaits a woman who is owned, and even a woman who is owned by no one.
.

we know our realness and rawness terrify you, our mothers and grandmothers and so many more. because the world you lived in punished you thoroughly for stepping outside the lines. your soul bears the scars to this day, but the fear never heals over. it rises again with each new danger we face.
.
even our ancient sisters long gone rise with this fear and rush to our side. they protect us and hold us and lift us up ... and yet they also tremble and shake with the rising of this fear. it reminds them of the soul wounds that cry out still to be seen and known and healed and freed.
.

and this is how we heal each other. mothers and sisters and all of us together, spirit and flesh, soul to soul, hand in hand we rise. and we rise. and we rise. and we rise. together we rise until every last one is free.
.
thank you @sdjun_creatives for the art.
.
.
.

text:
the past few days have made me so sad - as an american, as a woman, as a mother, as a survivor.
.
i focus on bear here, but this has so much to do with him, and with me. i worry about raising sons in a world where they need to understand caution and consent from an early age. play isn’t innocent anymore, and i worry that they will struggle with that - where a hug, or holding someone too long while wrestling or playing, will be problematic. and i agree that it should - that bodily autonomy and consent are so very important - but i worry that my sons will falter in the most minute and innocent of ways despite how they’ve been raised. i worry for them, and for their future, and i’m doing my best now to teach them so that it will be automatic. ask before hugging. be careful. keep your hands to yourself.
.
it’s something we model so often with bear. “can i give you a kiss?” he’ll move closer or away. and with his actions - “no, no hits. ouch! gentle,” followed by modeling.
.
i know that my experiences often guide how i raise my babies - the things i do, the perspectives i see, the views i have. i hope that these boys grow up to respect and be respected, to stand for what is right, and to be men of honor and integrity.
.
for now, i’ll hold them close, teach and protect, and love them fiercely. it’s really all i can do.
.
.
.
#realmomlife #thedailybear #motherhoodunplugged #metoo #motherhoodrising #sleepingbaby #raisingboys #lightroom #iphone #quietthechaos #holdthemoments

text:
honestly i’ve been a bit disconnected from the news this week after leaving england, then 24hrs with family and now booked solid in dubai, but what’s happening has not gone unnoticed plus i have been unable to sleep properly and been unusually tired since last week for no apparent reason... except what i now realise it to be, as the collective processing of so much trauma. the disconnection women feel from their bodies is a way to cope with the pain and stay safe. no wonder they have suppressed their voices. i’ve read some shocking things on posts, and it’s no wonder something like only 3% of cases get reported, who would want to go through what dr ford is putting herself through? and i think that’s why so many of us sweep it under the rug. there’s no need for details, but i’ve been there too, more than once... and at the time i haven’t even told friends or family and told myself a story that i was partly to blame...i just dealt with it (or didn’t) and carried on...
.
whatever happens, i hope it becomes safer for women as a result and the blatant misuse of power ends. .
the patriarchy is over and i will be doing whatever i can to support as many women as possible to regain their voices, reclaim their power and come back into their bodies. 💜🙌⭐️ .

text:
since dr. christine blasey ford came forward with her story, i have reeled and cringed as citizens and politicians show that the united states is a rape culture — meaning sexual assault is so common that it’s normalized and trivialized, while victims are blamed and disbelieved. yet in the midst of hard emotions and flashbacks sparked by the words of men in power, as a survivor, i feel a renewed strength and courage to live boldly and step into my power just as dr. blasey ford has done. i pray that my suffering, and the suffering of so many, will not be in vain; that these are the growing pains that allow our society to evolve out of darkness.
.
.
.

help is available 
national sexual assault hotline. free. confidential. 24/7.
call 800.656.hope

text_retweet:
#repost @causa_justa with @get_repost
・・・
#believesurvivors #grassrootsfeminists  statement from grassroots global justice: brett kavanaugh
is a virulent opponent of reproductive justice, lgbtq, and disability rights. these biases alone should discount him from consideration for the highest court of the federal government - a lifetime appointment. to add insult to injury, kavanaugh has also been accused of sexual assault and being a sexual predator by three women - one of whom, dr. christine blasey ford, is testifying in an open hearing today.

we believe dr. christine blasey ford. we believe deborah ramirez. we believe julie swetnick. we believe anita hill. we believe survivors. dr. blasey ford’s courage to step forward and speak about her own experience of sexual assault comes in the wake of the thousands of women and femmes speaking out against sexual harassment and violence with the #metoo movement. we know the tremendous strength it takes to speak our truths and fight for our survival.  it is our duty and moral obligation to stand with and center the voices and truths of sexual assault survivors. we honor the courage of our mothers, radical women of color, reproductive justice and anti-violence movement visionaries, and ancestors who organized, strategized and cleared paths of resistance for us, often under conditions of extreme duress and danger. we know that many of them could not tell their stories, and many survivors still cannot today. we are strengthened by the leadership of survivor advocates like anita hill and tarana burke, and are in solidarity with the #metoo movement as survivors ourselves.

text: i’m having such a hard time not losing my mind over what’s going on in our government. my heart is breaking for all these women who have come forth, crying out for justice. i cry for myself, seeing the current futility of it all, knowing that i could never get my own justice, even if i said anything.  i’ve been working on a superhero project, asking my coworkers who their favorite super hero is, but i get so sad when they ask mine. i love captain america for the ideals he represents: an america that stands up to the bullies, not one that encourages them. one that equips the little guy to fight. one that does what’s right, no matter what others may say or what the consequences may be. one that fights with a shield, not a gun. and maybe i’m being naive to think that we could have the purity of intention that cap does, but maybe i’m not. if we continue to fight for one another, to love each other fiercely, and to defend what we know to be right, then maybe we can affect some change in the world. or, at least, make our personal little corners of the world just that much safer. #metoo #ibelieveher #captainamerica #shield #nobullies #fighttogether #saynotokavanaugh #cryforjustice

text_retweet:
#repost via @kiersten.markham from @rachaelmaddox ・・・
hold your beloved. close and with care.
 rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth in speed and texture, poetry and metaphor.

ask her, how old do you feel, just right here, just right now? ask her, what does that part of you need to know, need to hear? ask her, how can i help you experience repair? – even if i wasn't the one who caused the pain. – even if i accidentally piled more on.

give her space and presence and care, so much care, until something exhales from the center of her pain. (non-poetically, let there be quiet and breathing and no words.

in the absence of your knowing what's going on for her, everything is coming together under her skin.) hold your beloved like the god of redemption is sending light through your willing hands, your steady chest, your loving eyes.

hold your beloved and let her cry and cry and cry

without needing to know why.

if you stay there, dear and willing, she will tell you everything, and you will believe her.

then, in your anger, in your concern, in your fear, you might feel the instinct to ask her if she could've done something differently.

not had those drinks. not smoked that pot. not gone out looking for love or lust or good conversation.

not gotten a job. not gone to the party. not had a god forsaken female body.

tonight, i beg of you – ask a different question:

what's going on with the men? 
you might want to ask, have you ever thought about reporting him?

and mostly, she'll say no. or yes, but... sometimes, she'll tell you how horrible it was.

tonight, i beg of you – ask a different question:

how can i support you? 
hold your beloved. close and with care. rest your ear to her heart. listen for its truth.

this is the first, most important thing you can do.

then tomorrow, put your own two hands on your very own heart and ask the god within, "where should i begin? use me move me make me a force for healing justice protection love." listen. listen. listen.

we needs your hands and your heart, your devotion to doing your part.

i know you want to. i know the king in there is in despair. the real repair is rising.

#metoo #healing

text: this is all i can think about this week. yes sexual assault, physical, emotional, spiritual assault leave deep wounds, and most are resilient, because we have to be. but the lack of support, when you come out about it... the questions, the “are you sure”, the dismissal... these are the wounds that last, that get cut open over and over. we need to support each other. we need to believe each other. we need to ask how we can be there for each other, and teach others how to be there. #metoo #ustoo #ibelieveher #ibelieveyou

text:
i’ve been away for some time retreating with a group who came seeking clarity in restoration at #dreamersquest, an entirely unplugged event and the first of its kind here. it was all that it was intended to be and more. 
returning to see all of these things about shithead #kavanaugh has me searching inside myself for the wisdom behind the 🔥anger🔥 so many are sharing about. 
meanwhile, got a little rage of my own stashed away for days like this. i’m guessing all women do. being a fan of getting it out on the table, i’ll take my turn. i’m glad to see so many women speaking the unspeakable.
for every time i’ve heard “can we stop using the term ‘toxic masculinity?”
for each catcall, proposition at work, comment on my ass, my “confirmation”, my beauty as they saw it/as it served them.
for each objectifying gesture, possessive remark, cleverly veiled misogyny.
for “feminazi”.
for every man i’ve been expected to admire or prove myself to, hardwired to please and seek approval from.
for the times i’ve been called “bitch” like it’s a bad thing.
for each time my precious resources have been exploited.
for every time i’ve been cornered or mishandled and had it pointed out to me that i caused it.
for the cage bars that keep us domestic and docile.
for every grabby, groping, drunken, sneering, abusive, sloppy, slobbering, hungry, threatening, hot-breathed joker i’ve crossed paths with.
🖕🏽
some days call for wisdom seeking and some just call for emptying out.
#stopkavanaugh #metoo #fuckthepatriarchy #donttellmetocalmdown

text: moon in gemini. the vocal chords, lungs & hands. something is bubbling up from the deepest dark babes. something new is trying to whisper to us. can you hear it? gemini, the twins. the duality, the light & the dark. we need both sides my loves. which part is missing for you? what magical alchemy is needed to close the schism? we’re disconnected from something we need, but what? this moon brings the potential to tap into our feelings, desires & purpose in a calm, logical way. as a grand air trine forms between the moon, the sun & mars our rational, curious natures may be activated. i know we’ve had a rough week but try to focus on innovation rn. look for the emergent properties in these broken bits & pieces. is there a solution within the sickness? can we heal our collective wounds by linking the masculine & the feminine back into one unified force? is there new information we’ve missed because there is a slight of hand game constantly going on before our eyes? two planets are about to change direction. pluto moves forward seeking to reveal profound transformations from our traumas hidden in our bones. venus turns back to show us how the darkness also offers us the sweetest sweetness. take time to notice what your pain has gifted you. look to your gemini house for the skills to process your experiences more like a machine. sometimes feelings matter most & sometimes they need to take the back seat. it is possible to think our way out in a healthy way but always ask for help. be the light & the dark. do something revolutionary, unexpected & unsettling. you’re already brave babes; now, be bold. “they” wrote the stories of our great-great-grandmothers mothers; it’s doesn’t mean they’re true. flip the script, change the narrative. rewrite the stories. dig deep inside you to find your magic & cast your spell now. you are powerful if you believe it to be so. your magic is real. speak your truest words, write them down, see them spread from your heart like telephone wires, like wifi signals. send them out to the kid inside of everyone. send 💗 out. beep, beeep! cast your spells & you may build a new foundation, a better altar for the future. i love you babes. i see you.
